        .destination-body-mobile
          Three glorious days in Medellín. Soak up the abundant sunshine, cheap food and friendly vibes. A delicious combination of nightlife, music, history, and culture, capped off by a full-day 5,000ft mountain bike descent...

      .row.col-md-6.destination-highlight
        .destination-image{style: "background: url('#{asset_path("background/rioverdethumbnail.jpg")}') center center no-repeat"}
          .destination-description
            .destination-title
              Rio Verde
            %a
              .destination-button{"data-num" => 2, "data-target" => "#myModal", "data-toggle" => "modal", 'data-name' => 'Basecamp1', 'data-title' => 'Testing the Waters on the Rio Verde', 'data-body' => 'If you don’t like getting wet, you’ve made a mistake and should turn back now. Day 4 marks the beginning of what I hope to be a ridiculous adventure and lifelong memory. To say you’re traveling to Colombia is cool. To say you’re traveling to Colombia for a whitewater rafting expedition is really really cool.<br><br>Our young, adventurous, and knowledgable guide Jules will pick us up from Medellín and drive us several hours to the source of the Rio Verde. With the help of some mules, we’ll hike down into the canyon and set up camp for the night. It won’t be “glamping”, but it also won’t be Bear Grylls-ing it . Accommodation for most of the journey is a hammock shelter with a mosquito net. In the most cliche way possible, we’ll bond around a glowing campfire, beer in hand, swapping stories of past adventures and revelling in the excitement of the day ahead.<br><br>As the name suggests, the Rio Verde is a beautiful shade of Emerald Green. It snakes its way through through lush mountain valleys, picking up steam as it merges with smaller streams along the way. We’ll spend 2 full days on the river passing small towns, hiking in the canyon, and swimming under waterfalls. Slightly more mellow than the second leg of our journey, the Rio Verde is a good opportunity to get comfortable with #RaftLife.', 'data-img-src' => "#{asset_url("background/rioverdethumbnail.jpg")}"}
                View Checkpoint
        .destination-subtitle-mobile
          Testing the Waters on the Rio Verde
        .destination-underline-mobile
        .destination-body-mobile
          Trace the Rio Verde from high mountain stream to rushing river. One part adrenaline, one part immersion, we’ll pass through rural villages, river fisherman and traditional gold miners along the way...

      .row.col-md-6.destination-highlight
        .destination-image{style: "background: url('#{asset_path("background/riosamanathumbnail.jpg")}') center center no-repeat"}
          .destination-description
            .destination-title
              Rio Samana
            %a
              .destination-button{"data-num" => 3, "data-target" => "#myModal", "data-toggle" => "modal", 'data-name' => 'Basecamp2', 'data-title' => 'Graduating to the Big Leagues of Whitewater', 'data-body' => "This mother of a river chews up and spits out inexperienced rafters on the daily. That is the line you’re expected to use when recounting the trip to friends when it’s over. In reality, the Rio Samana is bigger and badder than the Rio Verde, but still safe.<br><br>We’ll meet the Rio Samana after three days on the Rio Verde. Here is how Jules describes the river: “She is the mighty and powerful local river queen. Thousands of crystal clear creeks drop from high mountain peaks to cleanse the river basin and flow into pristine, iridescent blue swimming pools and cascading waterfalls. An awe-inspiring diversity of rare birds and butterflies can be observed at all times in her lowland tropical rainforest.” Sounds pretty cool to me...<br><br>We’ll go another 2 days on the Samana, spending the night in the home of a local friend and another night in a remote jungle camp. We can arrange to fish on the river or pan for gold. There will be plenty of hiking, swimming, card playing, and eating to round out the experience.", 'data-img-src' => "#{asset_url("background/riosamanathumbnail.jpg")}"}
                View Checkpoint
        .destination-subtitle-mobile
          Graduating to the Big Leagues of Whitewater
        .destination-underline-mobile
        .destination-body-mobile
          Tragically, our adventure might be one of the last on the Rio Samana, as a pending government proposal looks to dam this mighty river. We’ll learn from Jules about the political and environmental climate...

      .row.col-md-6.destination-highlight
        .destination-image{style: "background: url('#{asset_path("background/guatapethumbnail.jpeg")}') center center no-repeat"}
          .destination-description
            .destination-title
              Guatapé
            %a
              .destination-button{"data-num" => 4, "data-target" => "#myModal", "data-toggle" => "modal", 'data-name' => 'Basecamp3', 'data-title' => 'Rock Climbing in the Lake Country', 'data-body' => 'This glistening lake side town, will act as our base camp for several days. Formerly the summer retreat of Pablo Escobar and the cartel, this small town offers plenty of culture as well as adventure. Guatapé is a quaint village with colorful buildings and street side cafes. We’ll have the chance to kick back after a week of mostly adrenaline.<br><br>Other optional activities include a cocktail cruise on the expansive lake, renting scooters and riding through the countryside, or “playing paintball in one of Pablo Escobar’s bombed out country estates” (according to a hostel owner I chatted with). Point is, there are plenty of options individually or for us as a group.<br><br>The one activity we’re scheduled to do is rock climbing El Peñol. El Peñol is a 10,000,000 ton rock that juts out of the hillside behind Guatapé. It is typically submitted by a set of 747 steps, but I figured it would be more appropriate to climb it instead. We’ll watch the sunset at the top and take a cheesy group picture, which years from now you’ll look at, smile, and think to yourself, “damn... that was a great trip.”<br><br>Anyway, Guatape is our final stop and a flexible departure point. Rides are just an hour to the airport and can be arranged via bus or taxi. For those, who want to continue the adventure, buses run directly to Medellín which is another 30 minutes past the airport.', 'data-img-src' => "#{asset_url("background/guatapethumbnail.jpeg")}"}
                View Checkpoint
